1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:01,375
Day 16.

2
00:00:01,375 --> 00:00:03,694
I found a number in my account.

3
00:00:03,694 --> 00:00:05,569
Fifty-seven dollars.

4
00:00:05,569 --> 00:00:07,208
It was already gone.

5
00:00:07,208 --> 00:00:09,638
I hadn't lost a single trade yet.

6
00:00:09,638 --> 00:00:11,125
I can't code.

7
00:00:11,125 --> 00:00:13,180
9 years in crypto.

8
00:00:13,180 --> 00:00:15,527
AI trades my thousand.

9
00:00:15,527 --> 00:00:16,916
Day 16.

10
00:00:16,916 --> 00:00:20,902
For 15 days I'd been watching win rate and outcomes.

11
00:00:20,902 --> 00:00:26,402
62 trades, 48 percent — within what I thought was fixable.

12
00:00:26,402 --> 00:00:30,555
Then that afternoon I added another column — fees 30.

13
00:00:30,555 --> 00:00:32,375
Funding 27.

14
00:00:32,375 --> 00:00:35,347
Combined, 57 dollars.

15
00:00:35,347 --> 00:00:38,652
My real trading losses were only 14.

16
00:00:38,652 --> 00:00:46,319
Which means: even if I made zero mistakes, the account would still be bleeding — because holding a position costs rent.

17
00:00:46,319 --> 00:00:50,013
I'd stared at that 14 dollars for 15 days.

18
00:00:50,013 --> 00:00:55,319
The 57 that actually put me in the red was the column I hadn't looked at.

19
00:00:55,319 --> 00:00:59,680
If you optimize the wrong column, more effort makes it worse.

20
00:00:59,680 --> 00:01:04,805
Day 17 tomorrow — I shipped a rule I don't trust myself.

21
00:01:04,805 --> 00:01:06,194
Follow along.

